            <p>
              In today’s world, screens are everywhere. Phones, tablets, and TVs can easily become part of a toddler’s daily routine, especially when parents need a quiet moment, a peaceful car ride, or a simple way to keep little ones entertained.
            </p>

            <p>
              But toddlers also need time to explore the world with their hands. They need to touch, move, build, open, close, count, and discover. Screen-free play gives children the chance to develop important skills while staying active and curious.
            </p>

            <p>One simple way to encourage this kind of play is with a busy board.</p>
          </section>

          <section class="article-section">
            <div class="section-title">
              <span class="icon-badge">🌟</span>
              <h2>Why Screen-Free Play Matters</h2>
            </div>

            <p>
              Screen-free play allows toddlers to interact with real objects, textures, sounds, and movements. Instead of watching something happen on a screen, children get to create their own experience.
            </p>

            <p>
              They can try new actions, repeat favorite movements, and learn through trial and error. This type of play supports curiosity, independence, and confidence.
            </p>

            <p>
              Screen-free play can also help children practice patience. When a child works on opening a buckle or pulling a zipper, they are learning to focus on a task and keep trying.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="article-section">
            <div class="section-title">
              <span class="icon-badge">💡</span>
              <h2>What Makes Busy Boards So Useful?</h2>
            </div>

            <p>
              A busy board is filled with hands-on activities designed for little fingers. It may include buckles, zippers, buttons, laces, gears, numbers, letters, colors, and other interactive pieces.
            </p>

            <p>
              These features make busy boards both fun and purposeful. Children are drawn to the colors and movement, while parents appreciate that the activities support learning and practical skill-building.
            </p>

            <p>
              A busy board is not just a way to keep a toddler busy. It is a tool for meaningful play.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="article-section">
            <div class="section-title">
              <span class="icon-badge">🌱</span>
              <h2>Building Everyday Skills Through Play</h2>
            </div>

            <p>
              Toddlers love to copy the world around them. They see adults zip bags, fasten shoes, button shirts, open containers, and carry items. A busy board gives children a safe and playful way to practice similar movements.
            </p>

            <p>
              Activities like buckling, buttoning, tying, pulling, and counting can help toddlers build the foundation for real-life independence.
            </p>

            <p>These activities may support:</p>

            <ul>
              <li>Fine motor control</li>
              <li>Hand-eye coordination</li>
              <li>Early problem-solving</li>
              <li>Practical life skills</li>
              <li>Focus and concentration</li>
              <li>Confidence through repetition</li>
              <li>Independent play</li>
            </ul>

            <p>Small actions can lead to big developmental steps.</p>
          </section>

          <section class="article-section">
            <div class="section-title">
              <span class="icon-badge">🚗</span>
              <h2>A Helpful Toy for Travel and Quiet Moments</h2>
            </div>

            <p>
              Busy boards are especially useful for moments when parents need a calm activity. They are easy to bring along for car rides, flights, restaurants, waiting rooms, visits with family, or quiet play at home.
            </p>

            <p>
              Instead of reaching for a phone right away, parents can offer a busy board as an engaging alternative. The child gets something interactive to explore, and the parent gets a screen-free option that still keeps little hands busy.
            </p>

            <p>
              Because busy boards are portable, they can become part of a family’s everyday routine.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="article-section">
            <div class="section-title">
              <span class="icon-badge">🖐️</span>
              <h2>Encouraging Independent Play</h2>
            </div>

            <p>
              Independent play is an important part of toddler development. It gives children space to make choices, solve small problems, and explore without constant direction.
            </p>

            <p>
              Busy boards are great for this because they offer many activities in one place. A child can choose what to try first, move from one activity to another, and repeat the actions they enjoy most.
            </p>

            <p>
              This helps toddlers feel more in control of their play experience. Over time, that sense of independence can build confidence.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="article-section">
            <div class="section-title">
              <span class="icon-badge">🏠</span>
              <h2>How Parents Can Use Busy Boards at Home</h2>
            </div>

            <p>
              Busy boards can be used in simple ways throughout the day. Parents can offer them during quiet time, before meals, after nap time, or while preparing for a trip.
            </p>

            <p>You can also use a busy board as part of a short learning routine. For example:</p>

            <ul>
              <li>Count the beads together</li>
              <li>Name the colors on the board</li>
              <li>Practice opening and closing buckles</li>
              <li>Talk about shapes, letters, or numbers</li>
              <li>Encourage your child to try one new activity</li>
              <li>Celebrate small wins when they complete a task</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
              The goal is not to turn play into a lesson. The goal is to create moments of discovery.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="article-section">
            <div class="section-title">
              <span class="icon-badge">✨</span>
              <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
            </div>

            <p>
              Screen-free play does not have to be complicated. Sometimes, the best learning happens through simple activities that children can touch and explore.
            </p>

            <p>
              A busy board gives toddlers a playful way to build practical life skills, strengthen fine motor control, and stay engaged without relying on screens. It is portable, purposeful, and easy to include in everyday routines.
            </p>

            <p>
              For families looking for a thoughtful toy that supports learning through play, a busy board is a simple and meaningful choice.
